grounding, <hi>New Paths</hi> remains one of the most perceptive and inspiring<lb/>
of introductory guides.<lb/>
</p>
<p>Carter followed up on this book in two ways the same year. With<lb/>
Sadleir, he organized an exhibition “arranged to illustrate” <hi>New Paths</hi> at J. &amp; E. Bumpus, accompanied by a substantial annotated catalogue; and for<lb/>
the Scribner Book Store he put together a catalogue on detective fiction<lb/>
(largely from his own collection). (In the next few years, he and David A.<lb/>
Randall, head of Scribner’s Rare Book Department in New York as of<lb/>
March 1935, publicized many more new paths in their catalogues.) His<lb/>
interest in publishers’ bindings also led to further contributions to their<lb/>
history in the form of two introductions to Elkin Mathews catalogues<lb/>
(1932) and two small books, <hi>Publishers’ Cloth</hi> (1935, in connection with<lb/>
an exhibition at the New York Public Library) and <hi>More Binding Variants</hi><lb/>
(1938, a supplement to his 1932 book).<lb/>
</p>
<p>His editorial work also continued with editions of Housman’s <hi>Introductory Lecture</hi> (1933) and <hi>The Collected Poems</hi> (1939) and an incomplete<lb/>
